          "body": "The battle accounts in verses 14-15 and 17-18 are strikingly compressed. Joab advances — the Arameans flee. Abishai advances — the Ammonites flee. The fourfold repetition of 'flee' (nus) in verses 14-15 and 18 is not stylistic decoration; it is the Chronicler's theological signal. In Deuteronomy 28:7 God promises that enemies who rise against Israel will 'flee before you seven ways.' The flight of the Arameans before Joab and then before David personally is the visible fulfillment of that covenant word. The second engagement — after Aram reinforces with troops from beyond the Euphrates under Shophach (19:16) — is met by David himself crossing the Jordan with all Israel (19:17). The personal appearance of the covenant king is theologically weighted: David meets the largest threat with the full authority of his anointed office. The result is the death of Shophach and 47,000 Aramean casualties, followed by the total submission of Hadadezer's vassals to David's rule (19:19). The chapter that opened with David's servants humiliated ends with his enemies serving him."
