          "title": "The Chronicler's theological purpose — covenant vindicated",
          "body": "The Chronicler wrote for a post-exilic community whose confidence in the Davidic covenant had been shattered by the Babylonian destruction of Jerusalem and the temple. He preserves chapter 19 not as ancient military history but as covenant theology in narrative form. Every element supports the argument: David's chesed — even rejected — is not thwarted but vindicated. The two-front threat — even amplified by trans-Euphrates reinforcements — is not insurmountable but overcome. The covenant promise of 17:8-10 ('I will make your name like the names of the greatest men of the earth') is progressively fulfilled as the nations that assembled against David end the chapter serving him (19:19). For the Chronicler's post-exilic readers, who themselves faced the question of whether the Davidic covenant had any future, chapter 19 insists: the God who won these battles for David has not changed, and His covenant has not failed. The King who will fulfill the Davidic throne (Luke 1:32-33) stands in this same stream of rejected mercy, vindicated mission, and ultimate dominion over every enemy."
